"Gundelwein A., Müller-Lupp T., Sommerkorn M., Haupt E.T.K., Pfeiffer E.-M., Wiechmann H.","Carbon in tundra soils in the Lake Labaz region of arctic Siberia",2007,"European Journal of Soil Science","58","5",,"1164","1174",,,10.1111/j.1365-2389.2007.00908.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34548574863&partnerID=40&md5=a082cea78ed4cea86871542ad456f989","Council for the Lindau Nobel Laureate Meetings, 88131 Lindau (B), Germany; IFM-GEOMAR, Leibniz-Institute for Marine Science, 24148 Kiel, Germany; Macaulay Institute, Cragiebuckler, Aberdeen AB15 8QH, United Kingdom; Institute of Applied and Inorganic Chemistry, University of Hamburg, 20146 Hamburg, Germany; Institute of Soil Science, University of Hamburg, 20146 Hamburg, Germany","Gundelwein, A., Council for the Lindau Nobel Laureate Meetings, 88131 Lindau (B), Germany; Müller-Lupp, T., IFM-GEOMAR, Leibniz-Institute for Marine Science, 24148 Kiel, Germany; Sommerkorn, M., Macaulay Institute, Cragiebuckler, Aberdeen AB15 8QH, United Kingdom; Haupt, E.T.K., Institute of Applied and Inorganic Chemistry, University of Hamburg, 20146 Hamburg, Germany; Pfeiffer, E.-M., Institute of Soil Science, University of Hamburg, 20146 Hamburg, Germany; Wiechmann, H., Institute of Soil Science, University of Hamburg, 20146 Hamburg, Germany","Large amounts of carbon are stored in permafrost-affected soils of the Arctic tundra. The quantity, distribution and composition of this carbon are important, because much of the carbon is likely to be released as a result of global warming. We have studied soils of the central Siberian Arctic to determine the carbon content and the nature of the organic matter by density fractionation, and 13C-NMR- and 13C-stable-isotope analyses. There are pronounced differences in the profile and variations from place to place in the quantity and nature of soil organic matter. We estimated that the mean stock of carbon was 14.5 kg m-2 within the active layer. We found a total of about 30.7 kg C m-3 in the entire upper metre of the soils. Carbon of the tussock tundra showed strong vertical differentiation, with a large proportion comprising decomposed, recalcitrant compounds. We identified within the soil several zones of aerobe and anaerobe decomposition. Mobile carbon fractions have precipitated under the influence of low temperatures. © 2007 British Society of Soil Science.",,"carbon isotope; carbon sequestration; global warming; isotopic analysis; soil organic matter; source-sink dynamics; stable isotope; tundra soil; tussock grassland; Eurasia; Krasnoyarsk [Russian Federation]; Labaz Lake; Russian Federation; Siberia",,,,,,"Aleksandrova, V.D., (1980) The Arctic and Antarctic: Their Division into Geobotanical Areas., , Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; (2003) AMAP Assessment 2002: The Influence of Global Change on Contaminant Pathways To, Within, and from the Arctic., , AMAP. Arctic Monitoring and Assessment Programme (AMAP), Oslo; Von Baer, K.E., Materialien zur Kenntnis des unvergänglichen Boden-Eises in Sibirien. Unveröffentlichtes Typoskript (1840) Berichte und Arbeiten Aus der Universitätsbibliothek und Dem Universitätsarchiv Giessen, 51, pp. 1-234; Batjes, N.H., Total carbon and nitrogen in the soils of the world (1996) European Journal of Soil Science, 47, pp. 151-163; Beudert, G., (1988) Morphologische, Nasschemische und 13C-NMR-spektroskopische Kennzeichnung der Organischen Substanz Von Waldhumusprofilen Nach Dichtefraktionierung., , Bayreuther Bodenkundliche Berichte 8. Lehrstuhl für Bodenkunde und Bodengeographie, Bayreuth; Biryukova, O.N., Orlov, D.S., Reserves of organic matter and types of humus in soils and peats in the north of the European part of Russia (1993) Eurasian Soil Science, 25, pp. 26-42; (2003) Circumpolar Arctic Vegetation Map. Scale 1: 7.500.000. Conservation of Arctic Flora and Fauna (CAFF) Map No 1., , CAVM. US Fish and Wildlife Service, Anchorage, Alaska; Grishina, L.A., Todorova, N.I., Frakzionii sostaw gumusa pu